, Red Sea, 
<collectingCountry id="2FAC760BFF95FFBF94A01C0DF726FD9B" box="[151,277,548,573]" name="Philippines" pageId="7" pageNumber="332">Philippines</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="332A4B6AFF95FFBF95141C0DF475FD9B" author="Newman" box="[291,582,548,573]" pageId="7" pageNumber="332" refString="Newman, L. J. &amp; Cannon, L. R. G. (2005) Fabulous flatworms: a guide to marine polyclads. ABRS and CSIRO Publishing, Canberra and Melbourne, Australia. CD-ROM interactive guide." type="book" year="2005">
Newman &amp; Cannon 
<number id="E17324BCFF95FFBF963B1C0DF475FD9B" box="[524,582,548,573]" pageId="7" pageNumber="332" value="2005.0">2005</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5704369BFF95FFBF94F01C6EF7CDFD6A" blockId="7.[151,1437,476,861]" pageId="7" pageNumber="332">
<emphasis id="65CFEA89FF95FFBF94F01C6EF7A4FDC6" bold="true" box="[199,407,583,608]" pageId="7" pageNumber="332">
Location in 
<collectingCountry id="2FAC760BFF95FFBF956C1C6EF7A1FDC6" box="[347,402,583,608]" name="Iran" pageId="7" pageNumber="332">Iran</collectingCountry>
.
</emphasis>
Sampling locality composed of rocky substrate, with numerous small and large intertidal pools covered with red and brown algae, ascidians and sponges. Specimens sparsely distributed, collected from under rocks, associated with didemnid ascidians (
<figureCitation id="CF802A1EFF95FFBF96F31CA6F524FD0E" box="[708,791,655,680]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1356,1378]" captionTargetBox="[158,1429,198,1329]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[151,1436,193,1334]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 10. Field photography of Iranian polyclads presented here: (A – C) marine polyclads associated with ascidians (A) Maritigrella makranica (B) Pseudobiceros uniarborensis (C) Thysanozoon brocchii (D) Tytthosoceros lizardensis along with red algae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/249717/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="332">
Fig. 
<number id="E17324BCFF95FFBF96CE1CB9F524FD0E" box="[761,791,656,680]" pageId="7" pageNumber="332" value="10.0">10</number>
</figureCitation>
B), were observed only in the coasts of the Gulf of 
<collectingCountry id="2FAC760BFF95FFBF916F1CB9F3AEFD0E" box="[1368,1437,656,680]" name="Oman" pageId="7" pageNumber="332">Oman</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="CF802A1EFF95FFBF94A81C9DF6D1FD6A" box="[159,226,692,717]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,844,866]" captionTargetBox="[153,1434,208,818]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,195,822]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Map of the Western Indo-Pacific including the Persian Gulf and Gulf of Oman. Sampling stations are indicated by numbers (stations 30 – 35 located at Qeshm Island)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/249708/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="332">
Fig. 
<number id="E17324BCFF95FFBF94E31C9DF6D1FD6A" box="[212,226,692,716]" pageId="7" pageNumber="332" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
station 
<number id="E17324BCFF95FFBF950D1C9DF76BFD6B" box="[314,344,692,717]" pageId="7" pageNumber="332" value="36.0">36</number>
, and Table. 
<number id="E17324BCFF95FFBF95E81C9DF7DFFD6A" box="[479,492,692,716]" pageId="7" pageNumber="332" value="1.0">1</number>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5704369BFF95FFBF94F01CFEF506FCFB" blockId="7.[151,1437,476,861]" pageId="7" pageNumber="332">
<emphasis id="65CFEA89FF95FFBF94F01CFEF782FD56" bold="true" box="[199,433,727,752]" pageId="7" pageNumber="332">Material examined.</emphasis>
Four live specimens were examined 
<emphasis id="65CFEA89FF95FFBF97631CF0F596FD56" box="[852,933,729,752]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="332">in vitro</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="CF802A1EFF95FFBF97821CFEF5C8FD56" box="[949,1019,727,752]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1650,1672]" captionTargetBox="[270,1319,918,1624]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[266,1320,913,1629]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Pseudobiceros uniarborensis. Live specimens." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/249711/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="332">
Fig. 
<number id="E17324BCFF95FFBF97DD1CF1F5C8FD56" box="[1002,1019,728,752]" pageId="7" pageNumber="332" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
). Unfortunately all of them were lost during fixation, so histological serial sections were not prepared. In 
<taxonomicName id="90BB4D18FF95FFBF97891CD5F251FCB3" box="[958,1122,764,789]" class="Turbellaria" family="Pseudocerotidae" genus="Pseudobiceros" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polycladida" pageId="7" pageNumber="332" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="65CFEA89FF95FFBF97891CD5F251FCB3" box="[958,1122,764,789]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="332">Pseudobiceros</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the dorsal color pattern is taxonomically more important than the details of the reproductive anatomy (
<bibRefCitation id="332A4B6AFF95FFBF90791D09F3A3FC9E" author="Newman" box="[1102,1424,800,824]" pageId="7" pageNumber="332" refString="Newman, L. J. &amp; Cannon, L. R. G. (1997) Nine new species of Pseudobiceros (Platyhelminthes: Polycladida) from the Indo- Pacific. Raffles Bulletin of Zoology, 45, 341 - 368." type="journal article" year="1997">
Newman &amp; Cannon 
<number id="E17324BCFF95FFBF91631D09F3A3FC9E" box="[1364,1424,800,824]" pageId="7" pageNumber="332" value="1997.0">1997</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Consequently the identification was based on this trait only.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption id="03C46613FF95FFBF94A0185BF4C2F92E" box="[151,753,1650,1672]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/249711/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="332" targetBox="[270,1319,918,1624]" targetPageId="7">
<paragraph id="5704369BFF95FFBF94A0185BF4C2F92E" blockId="7.[151,753,1650,1672]" box="[151,753,1650,1672]" pageId="7" pageNumber="332">
<emphasis id="65CFEA89FF95FFBF94A0185BF721F921" bold="true" box="[151,274,1650,1672]" pageId="7" pageNumber="332">FIGURE 4.</emphasis>
<emphasis id="65CFEA89FF95FFBF952E185BF474F92E" box="[281,583,1650,1672]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="332">
<taxonomicName id="90BB4D18FF95FFBF952E185BF471F92E" box="[281,578,1650,1672]" class="Turbellaria" family="Pseudocerotidae" genus="Pseudobiceros" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polycladida" pageId="7" pageNumber="332" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="uniarborensis">Pseudobiceros uniarborensis</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Live specimens.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<subSubSection id="1FA16510FF95FFBF94F01886F2DAF806" pageId="7" pageNumber="332" type="description">
<paragraph id="5704369BFF95FFBF94F01886F2DAF806" blockId="7.[151,1437,1711,2027]" pageId="7" pageNumber="332">
<emphasis id="65CFEA89FF95FFBF94F01886F76AF96E" bold="true" box="[199,345,1711,1736]" pageId="7" pageNumber="332">Description.</emphasis>
Living animals with delicate body, highly ruffled margin, dark brown; dorsal surface with three narrow marginal bands: inner band bright orange, followed by a wide clear band, and a whitish grey rim. The ventral side is brown with a white marginal band. Size of the living specimens, at rest, 
<quantity id="90439B7EFF95FFBF904A18D1F285F8A9" box="[1149,1206,1784,1808]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="332" unit="cm" value="3.0">3 cm</quantity>
× 
<quantity id="90439B7EFF95FFBF90E018D1F323F8A9" box="[1239,1296,1784,1808]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="332" unit="cm" value="1.0">1 cm</quantity>
(in smallest specimen) to 
<quantity id="90439B7EFF95FFBF95191932F749F895" box="[302,378,1819,1844]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" pageId="7" pageNumber="332" unit="cm" value="5.5">5.5 cm</quantity>
× 
<quantity id="90439B7EFF95FFBF95AE1932F7D6F895" box="[409,485,1819,1844]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6" pageId="7" pageNumber="332" unit="cm" value="1.6">1.6 cm</quantity>
(in largest specimen) (
<figureCitation id="CF802A1EFF95FFBF96D01932F51FF892" box="[743,812,1819,1844]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1650,1672]" captionTargetBox="[270,1319,918,1624]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[266,1320,913,1629]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Pseudobiceros uniarborensis. Live specimens." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/249711/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="332">
Fig. 
<number id="E17324BCFF95FFBF972C1935F51FF892" box="[795,812,1820,1844]" pageId="7" pageNumber="332" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
). The pseudotentacles are ear-like, and are held erect in live animals, 
<quantity id="90439B7EFF95FFBF951A1916F7B1F8F1" box="[301,386,1855,1880]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.6" pageId="7" pageNumber="332" unit="mm" value="2.6">2.6 mm</quantity>
long, dark brown without marginal bands, with white tip, and a white-grey triangle extending to the cerebral eyespots (
<figureCitation id="CF802A1EFF95FFBF9582194AF7CFF8DA" box="[437,508,1891,1916]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1650,1672]" captionTargetBox="[270,1319,918,1624]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[266,1320,913,1629]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Pseudobiceros uniarborensis. Live specimens." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/249711/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="332">
Fig. 
<number id="E17324BCFF95FFBF95DC194DF7CFF8DA" box="[491,508,1892,1916]" pageId="7" pageNumber="332" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
); the cerebral cluster made up of about 
<number id="E17324BCFF95FFBF97F2194AF5D2F8DA" box="[965,993,1891,1916]" pageId="7" pageNumber="332" value="63.0">63</number>
eyespots; the pharynx is typical of the genus, with simple folds. In ventral view the two male gonopores are situated close to one another.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="1FA16510FF95FFB094F01982F52FFCFB" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="333" pageId="7" pageNumber="332" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="5704369BFF95FFB094F01982F48CFE2E" blockId="7.[151,1437,1711,2027]" lastBlockId="8.[151,1437,151,861]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="333" pageId="7" pageNumber="332">
<emphasis id="65CFEA89FF95FFBF94F01982F708F862" bold="true" box="[199,315,1963,1988]" pageId="7" pageNumber="332">Remarks.</emphasis>
Prior to 
<number id="E17324BCFF95FFBF95981985F7D9F862" box="[431,490,1964,1988]" pageId="7" pageNumber="332" value="1984.0">1984</number>
, polyclad taxonomists believed that the majority of conspicuous and colorful pseudocerotid flatworms belonged to the genus 
<taxonomicName id="90BB4D18FF95FFBF968A19FBF5EAF84D" authority="Lang, 1884" authorityName="Lang" authorityYear="1884" box="[701,985,2002,2027]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Pseudoceritidae" genus="Pseudoceros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polycladida" pageId="7" pageNumber="332" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="65CFEA89FF95FFBF968A19FBF578F84D" box="[701,843,2002,2027]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="332">Pseudoceros</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="332A4B6AFF95FFBF976319FAF5EAF84D" author="Lang" box="[852,985,2003,2027]" pageId="7" pageNumber="332" refString="Lang, A. (1884) Fauna und Flora des Golfes von Neapel. Monogr. 11. Die Polycladen (Seeplanarien) des Golfes von Neapel und der angrenzenden Meeresabschnitte. Engelmann, Leipzig, 668 pp. [Germany]" type="book" year="1884">
Lang, 
<number id="E17324BCFF95FFBF97A919FAF5EAF84D" box="[926,985,2003,2027]" pageId="7" pageNumber="332" value="1884.0">1884</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation id="332A4B6AFF95FFBF97D019FBF2A0F84D" author="Faubel" box="[999,1171,2002,2027]" pageId="7" pageNumber="332" refString="Faubel, A. (1984 a) The Polycladida, Turbellaria. Proposal and establishment of a new system. Part II. The Cotylea. Mitteilungen aus dem Hamburgischen Zoologischen Museum und Institut, 81, 189 - 259." type="journal article" year="1984" yearSuffix="a">
Faubel (
<number id="E17324BCFF95FFBF907319FAF24DF84D" box="[1092,1150,2003,2027]" pageId="7" pageNumber="332" value="1984.0">1984</number>
a)
</bibRefCitation>
erected the new genus 
<taxonomicName id="90BB4D18FF9AFFB094A01EBEF708FF16" box="[151,315,151,176]" class="Turbellaria" family="Pseudocerotidae" genus="Pseudobiceros" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polycladida" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="65CFEA89FF9AFFB094A01EBEF708FF16" box="[151,315,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="333">Pseudobiceros</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and transferred all 
<taxonomicName id="90BB4D18FF9AFFB0962D1EBEF49BFF16" box="[538,680,151,176]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Pseudoceritidae" genus="Pseudoceros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polycladida" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="65CFEA89FF9AFFB0962D1EBEF49BFF16" box="[538,680,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="333">Pseudoceros</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species with double male systems into the new genus. Since then, 
<taxonomicName id="90BB4D18FF9AFFB094A01E95F708FF73" box="[151,315,188,213]" class="Turbellaria" family="Pseudocerotidae" genus="Pseudobiceros" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polycladida" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="65CFEA89FF9AFFB094A01E95F708FF73" box="[151,315,188,213]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="333">Pseudobiceros</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been further validated by traits such as pharynx 
<typeStatus id="88008839FF9AFFB097B31E94F584FF73" box="[900,951,189,213]" pageId="8" pageNumber="333">type</typeStatus>
, arrangement of cerebral eyes, ruffled body margin and molecular data (
<bibRefCitation id="332A4B6AFF9AFFB095EE1EF6F53AFF5E" author="Litvaitis" box="[473,777,223,248]" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" refString="Litvaitis, M. K. &amp; Newman, L. J. (2001) Molecular framework for the phylogeny of the Pseudocerotidae (Platyhelminthes, Polycladida). Hydrobiologia, 444, 177 - 182." type="journal article" year="2001">
Litvaitis &amp; Newman 
<number id="E17324BCFF9AFFB096F91EC9F53AFF5E" box="[718,777,224,248]" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" value="2001.0">2001</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="332A4B6AFF9AFFB097201EC9F273FF5E" author="Newman" box="[791,1088,224,248]" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" refString="Newman, L. J. &amp; Cannon, L. R. G. (1997) Nine new species of Pseudobiceros (Platyhelminthes: Polycladida) from the Indo- Pacific. Raffles Bulletin of Zoology, 45, 341 - 368." type="journal article" year="1997">
Newman &amp; Cannon 
<number id="E17324BCFF9AFFB090321EC9F273FF5E" box="[1029,1088,224,248]" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" value="1997.0">1997</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="332A4B6AFF9AFFB0907A1EF6F3A2FF5E" author="Rawlinson" box="[1101,1425,223,248]" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" refString="Rawlinson, K. A. &amp; Litvaitis, M. K. (2008) Cotylea (Polycladida): a cladistic analysis of morphology. Invertebrate Biology, 127 (2), 121 - 138. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1744 - 7410.2007.00119. x" type="journal article" year="2008">
Rawlinson &amp; Litvaitis 
<number id="E17324BCFF9AFFB091631EC9F3A2FF5E" box="[1364,1425,224,248]" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" value="2008.0">2008</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Within species of 
<taxonomicName id="90BB4D18FF9AFFB095451F2DF425FEBB" box="[370,534,260,285]" class="Turbellaria" family="Pseudocerotidae" genus="Pseudobiceros" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polycladida" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="65CFEA89FF9AFFB095451F2DF425FEBB" box="[370,534,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="333">Pseudobiceros</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, color patterns have more taxonomic value than details of the reproductive anatomy (
<bibRefCitation id="332A4B6AFF9AFFB095301F01F41CFEE6" author="Newman" box="[263,559,296,320]" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" refString="Newman, L. J. &amp; Cannon, L. R. G. (1997) Nine new species of Pseudobiceros (Platyhelminthes: Polycladida) from the Indo- Pacific. Raffles Bulletin of Zoology, 45, 341 - 368." type="journal article" year="1997">
Newman &amp; Cannon 
<number id="E17324BCFF9AFFB095C31F01F41CFEE6" box="[500,559,296,320]" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" value="1997.0">1997</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), a view that has been demonstrated by molecular data (
<bibRefCitation id="332A4B6AFF9AFFB090861F0EF6E0FEC2" author="Litvaitis" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" refString="Litvaitis, M. K. &amp; Newman, L. J. (2001) Molecular framework for the phylogeny of the Pseudocerotidae (Platyhelminthes, Polycladida). Hydrobiologia, 444, 177 - 182." type="journal article" year="2001">
Litvaitis &amp; Newman 
<number id="E17324BCFF9AFFB094A01F65F6E0FEC2" box="[151,211,332,356]" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" value="2001.0">2001</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="332A4B6AFF9AFFB094E81F64F436FEC2" author="Newman" box="[223,517,332,356]" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" refString="Newman, L. J. &amp; Cannon, L. R. G. (1994) Pseudoceros and Pseudobiceros (Platyhelminthes, Polycladida, Pseudocerotidae) from Eastern Australia and Papua New Guinea. Memoirs of the Queensland Museum, 37, 205 - 266." type="journal article" year="1994">
Newman &amp; Cannon 
<number id="E17324BCFF9AFFB095FE1F65F436FEC2" box="[457,517,332,356]" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" value="1994.0">1994</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="332A4B6AFF9AFFB096261F65F47FFEC3" author="Newman" box="[529,588,332,357]" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" refString="Newman, L. J. &amp; Cannon, L. R. G. (1995) Colour pattern variation in the tropical flatworm, Pseudoceros (Platyhelminthes, Polycladida). The Raffles Bulletin of Zoology, 43, 435 - 446." type="journal article" year="1995">
<number id="E17324BCFF9AFFB096261F65F47FFEC3" box="[529,588,332,357]" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" value="1995.0">1995</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="332A4B6AFF9AFFB0966E1F65F4A6FEC2" author="Newman" box="[601,661,332,356]" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" refString="Newman, L. J. &amp; Cannon, L. R. G. (1997) Nine new species of Pseudobiceros (Platyhelminthes: Polycladida) from the Indo- Pacific. Raffles Bulletin of Zoology, 45, 341 - 368." type="journal article" year="1997">
<number id="E17324BCFF9AFFB0966E1F65F4A6FEC2" box="[601,661,332,356]" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" value="1997.0">1997</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). It is therefore essential to examine live specimens and record their color patterns 
<emphasis id="65CFEA89FF9AFFB095001F58F7B0FE2E" box="[311,387,369,392]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="333">in vivo</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="332A4B6AFF9AFFB095A61F59F480FE2E" author="Newman" box="[401,691,367,392]" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" refString="Newman, L. J. &amp; Schupp, P. (2002) A new species of pseudocerotid flatworm (Platyhelminthes, Poly cladida) from the Indo- Pacific. Micronesica, 34 (2), 177 - 184." type="journal article" year="2002">
Newman &amp; Schupp 
<number id="E17324BCFF9AFFB096411F59F480FE2E" box="[630,691,368,392]" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" value="2002.0">2002</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5704369BFF9AFFB094F01FBCF505FD0E" blockId="8.[151,1437,151,861]" pageId="8" pageNumber="333">
To date, 
<number id="E17324BCFF9AFFB095191FBDF779FE0A" box="[302,330,404,428]" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" value="37.0">37</number>
species of 
<taxonomicName id="90BB4D18FF9AFFB095E61FBDF446FE0B" box="[465,629,404,429]" class="Turbellaria" family="Pseudocerotidae" genus="Pseudobiceros" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polycladida" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="65CFEA89FF9AFFB095E61FBDF446FE0B" box="[465,629,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="333">Pseudobiceros</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have been described (
<bibRefCitation id="332A4B6AFF9AFFB0974C1FBDF213FE0A" author="Bolanos" box="[891,1056,404,429]" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" refString="Bolanos, D. M. (2010) Polycladida lifedesks. Available from: http: // polycladida. lifedesks. org / pages / 3179 (accessed 5 June 2012)" type="journal article" year="2010">
Bolaños 
<number id="E17324BCFF9AFFB097D41FBDF213FE0A" box="[995,1056,404,428]" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" value="2010.0">2010</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="90BB4D18FF9AFFB090021FBCF2DCFE0B" box="[1077,1263,404,429]" class="Turbellaria" family="Pseudocerotidae" genus="Pseudobiceros" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polycladida" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="uniarborensis">
<emphasis id="65CFEA89FF9AFFB090021FBCF2DCFE0B" box="[1077,1263,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="333">P. uniarborensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was originally described as opaque black in color with three extremely narrow marginal bands (
<bibRefCitation id="332A4B6AFF9AFFB090151F91F37BFE76" author="Newman" box="[1058,1352,440,464]" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" refString="Newman, L. J. &amp; Cannon, L. R. G. (1994) Pseudoceros and Pseudobiceros (Platyhelminthes, Polycladida, Pseudocerotidae) from Eastern Australia and Papua New Guinea. Memoirs of the Queensland Museum, 37, 205 - 266." type="journal article" year="1994">
Newman &amp; Cannon 
<number id="E17324BCFF9AFFB0913B1F91F37BFE76" box="[1292,1352,440,464]" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" value="1994.0">1994</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Later, it was shown that this species shows a range of color patterns around the world including black with irregular white spots (
<collectingCountry id="2FAC760BFF9AFFB094D11FD6F760FDBE" box="[230,339,511,536]" name="Australia" pageId="8" pageNumber="333">Australia</collectingCountry>
); semi-transparent brown with or without irregular white spots (
<collectingCountry id="2FAC760BFF9AFFB0906F1C29F377FDBE" box="[1112,1348,511,536]" name="Papua New Guinea" pageId="8" pageNumber="333">Papua New Guinea</collectingCountry>
); semitransparent, and light brown (the 
<collectingCountry id="2FAC760BFF9AFFB0962D1C0DF4A9FD9B" box="[538,666,548,573]" name="Philippines" pageId="8" pageNumber="333">Philippines</collectingCountry>
) (
<bibRefCitation id="332A4B6AFF9AFFB096851C0DF5D3FD9A" author="Newman" box="[690,992,548,572]" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" refString="Newman, L. J. &amp; Cannon, L. R. G. (1997) Nine new species of Pseudobiceros (Platyhelminthes: Polycladida) from the Indo- Pacific. Raffles Bulletin of Zoology, 45, 341 - 368." type="journal article" year="1997">
Newman &amp; Cannon 
<number id="E17324BCFF9AFFB097931C0DF5D3FD9A" box="[932,992,548,572]" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" value="1997.0">1997</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Based on the color and color pattern categorization of 
<bibRefCitation id="332A4B6AFF9AFFB095541C61F480FDC6" author="Newman" box="[355,691,583,608]" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" refString="Newman, L. J. &amp; Cannon, L. R. G. (1994) Pseudoceros and Pseudobiceros (Platyhelminthes, Polycladida, Pseudocerotidae) from Eastern Australia and Papua New Guinea. Memoirs of the Queensland Museum, 37, 205 - 266." type="journal article" year="1994">
Newman and Cannon (
<number id="E17324BCFF9AFFB096471C61F499FDC6" box="[624,682,584,608]" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" value="1994.0">1994</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
the specimens found in the present study belong to the second group. In terms of their color pattern, our specimens also closely resemble those shown in the multimedia CD by 
<bibRefCitation id="332A4B6AFF9AFFB094A01CB9F7EEFD0E" author="Newman" box="[151,477,655,680]" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" refString="Newman, L. J. &amp; Cannon, L. R. G. (2005) Fabulous flatworms: a guide to marine polyclads. ABRS and CSIRO Publishing, Canberra and Melbourne, Australia. CD-ROM interactive guide." type="book" year="2005">
Newman and Cannon (
<number id="E17324BCFF9AFFB095AE1CA6F7E5FD0E" box="[409,470,655,680]" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" value="2005.0">2005</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, originating from the Red Sea.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5704369BFF9AFFB094F91C9CF52FFCFB" blockId="8.[151,1437,151,861]" pageId="8" pageNumber="333">
<taxonomicName id="90BB4D18FF9AFFB094F91C9CF7B6FD6B" box="[206,389,692,717]" class="Turbellaria" family="Pseudocerotidae" genus="Pseudobiceros" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polycladida" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="uniarborensis">
<emphasis id="65CFEA89FF9AFFB094F91C9CF7B6FD6B" box="[206,389,692,717]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="333">P. uniarborensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is recorded for the first time from the Gulf of 
<collectingCountry id="2FAC760BFF9AFFB097A71C9DF5E4FD6A" box="[912,983,692,716]" name="Oman" pageId="8" pageNumber="333">Oman</collectingCountry>
, extending the geographical distribution from the Red Sea (
<bibRefCitation id="332A4B6AFF9AFFB0955F1CF1F4B9FD56" author="Newman" box="[360,650,727,752]" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" refString="Newman, L. J. &amp; Cannon, L. R. G. (2005) Fabulous flatworms: a guide to marine polyclads. ABRS and CSIRO Publishing, Canberra and Melbourne, Australia. CD-ROM interactive guide." type="book" year="2005">
Newman &amp; Cannon 
<number id="E17324BCFF9AFFB096671CFEF4B9FD56" box="[592,650,727,752]" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" value="2005.0">2005</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) to the Western Indian Ocean. Considering the uncommon occurrence of this species in the Gulf of 
<collectingCountry id="2FAC760BFF9AFFB095EF1CD5F42EFCB2" box="[472,541,764,788]" name="Oman" pageId="8" pageNumber="333">Oman</collectingCountry>
and not in the Persian Gulf, it seems that 
<taxonomicName id="90BB4D18FF9AFFB097DB1CD4F291FCB3" box="[1004,1186,764,789]" class="Turbellaria" family="Pseudocerotidae" genus="Pseudobiceros" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polycladida" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="uniarborensis">
<emphasis id="65CFEA89FF9AFFB097DB1CD4F291FCB3" box="[1004,1186,764,789]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="333">P. uniarborensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is sparsely distributed along the Iranian coasts, maybe due to different physico-chemical environment of the Persian Gulf compared with the Gulf of 
<collectingCountry id="2FAC760BFF9AFFB0952E1D6DF76DFCFA" box="[281,350,836,860]" name="Oman" pageId="8" pageNumber="333">Oman</collectingCountry>
as mentioned above for 
<emphasis id="65CFEA89FF9AFFB096461D6CF52FFCFB" box="[625,796,836,861]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="333">
<taxonomicName id="90BB4D18FF9AFFB096461D6CF522FCFB" box="[625,785,836,861]" class="Turbellaria" family="Euryleptidae" genus="Maritigrella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polycladida" pageId="8" pageNumber="333" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="makranica">M. makranica</taxonomicName>
..
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
